SIMPLE: twelve
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Twelve
<hw>Twelve</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>twelve</ets>,
<ets>twelf</ets>, AS. <ets>twelf</ets>; akin to OFries.
<ets>twelf</ets>, <ets>twelef</ets>, <ets>twilif</ets>, OS.
<ets>twelif</ets>, D. <ets>twaalf</ets>, G. <ets>zw⟦oum⟧lf</ets>, OHG.
<ets>zwelif</ets>, Icel. <ets>t⟦omac⟧lf</ets>, Sw. <ets>tolf</ets>, Dan.
<ets>tolv</ets>, Goth. <ets>twalif</ets>, from the root of E.
<ets>two</ets> + the same element as in the second part of E.
<ets>eleven</ets>. See <er>Two</er>, and <er>Eleven</er>.]</ety>
<def>One more that eleven; two and ten; twice six; a dozen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Twelve-men's morris</b></col>. <cd>See the Note under
<er>Morris</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Twelve Tables</b></col>. <fld>(Rom.
Antiq.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Table</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twelve</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Twelve
<hw>Twelve</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The number next
following eleven; the sum of ten and two, or of twice six; twelve units
or objects; a dozen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A symbol representing twelve units, as 12, or
xii.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The Twelve</b></col> <fld>(Script.)</fld>, <cd>the twelve
apostles.</cd> <rj><au>Matt. xxvi. 20.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twelvemo</ent>⟦br⟧
